              <h2>How this Project ROI Calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is designed for project managers, PMOs, and business
                leaders who need a quick but robust way to evaluate project
                economics. It goes beyond a simple ROI percentage by including
                payback period, NPV, benefit–cost ratio, and an approximate
                internal rate of return (IRR).
              </p>

              <h3>1. Simple vs. detailed cash flow modes</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple totals</strong> – Ideal for early-stage
                  estimates. You enter:
                  <ul>
                    <li>Upfront costs (period 0)</li>
                    <li>Ongoing cost per period</li>
                    <li>Benefit per period</li>
                    <li>Residual value at the end of the horizon</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cash flow by period</strong> – For more accurate
                  business cases. You specify costs and benefits for each period
                  individually (e.g., year 0–5 or month 0–24).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Core formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Net benefit</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Net benefit} = \text{Total benefits} - \text{Total
                  costs} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>ROI (%)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{ROI} = \frac{\text{Net benefit}}{\text{Total costs}}
                  \times 100 \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Net present value (NPV)</strong></p>
                <p>\[ \text{NPV} = \sum_{t=0}^{N} \frac{CF_t}{(1+r)^{t}} \]</p>
                <p>
                  where \(CF_t\) is the net cash flow in period \(t\), \(r\) is
                  the discount rate per period, and \(N\) is the number of
                  periods.
                </p>
              </div>

              <p>
                <strong>Payback period</strong> is computed by accumulating cash
                flows until the cumulative total becomes positive. If the sign
                flips within a period, we interpolate linearly to estimate the
                fractional period.
              </p>

              <p>
                <strong>IRR (internal rate of return)</strong> is approximated
                numerically by searching for the discount rate that makes NPV ≈
                0. If the cash flows are irregular or multiple sign changes
                occur, IRR may not exist or may be ambiguous; in those cases the
                tool may show “N/A”.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Discount rate and period type</h3>
              <p>
                The discount rate you enter is annual. If you choose monthly
                periods, the calculator converts the annual rate
                \(r_{\text{year}}\) to an effective monthly rate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ r_{\text{month}} = (1 + r_{\text{year}})^{1/12} - 1 \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This ensures that NPV and IRR are consistent with the time scale
                you select.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Risk-adjusted benefits</h3>
              <p>
                To avoid overly optimistic business cases, you can apply a
                <strong>risk adjustment</strong> to benefits. If you enter a
                risk adjustment of 20%, the calculator multiplies all benefits
                by 0.8 before computing ROI and NPV:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Adjusted benefits} = \text{Benefits} \times (1 -
                  \text{Risk\%}/100) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example: IT system implementation</h3>
              <p>Suppose you are evaluating a 3-year IT project with:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Upfront cost: $120,000</li>
                <li>Ongoing cost: $20,000 per year</li>
                <li>
                  Benefits: $80,000 per year (cost savings + extra revenue)
                </li>
                <li>Residual value: $0</li>
                <li>Discount rate: 10% per year</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Over 3 years:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total costs = 120,000 + 3 × 20,000 = 180,000</li>
                <li>Total benefits = 3 × 80,000 = 240,000</li>
                <li>Net benefit = 240,000 − 180,000 = 60,000</li>
                <li>ROI = 60,000 ÷ 180,000 ≈ 33.3%</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator will also show the payback period (somewhere in
                year 2) and NPV at 10%.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about project ROI</h2>

              <h3>What is project ROI?</h3>
              <p>
                Project ROI (Return on Investment) is a financial metric that
                compares the net benefit of a project to its total cost. It
                helps you answer: “For every dollar we invest in this project,
                how much do we get back?”
              </p>

              <h3>What costs should I include?</h3>
              <p>
                Include all incremental costs that occur because of the project,
                such as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Planning and design</li>
                <li>Software licenses and subscriptions</li>
                <li>Hardware and infrastructure</li>
                <li>Implementation and integration</li>
                <li>Training and change management</li>
                <li>Ongoing support, maintenance, and additional staffing</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>What benefits should I include?</h3>
              <p>
                Convert all benefits to monetary terms where possible,
                including:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>New revenue or higher prices</li>
                <li>Cost savings (labor, materials, overhead)</li>
                <li>Productivity gains (time saved × hourly cost)</li>
                <li>Risk reduction (expected loss avoided)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Non-financial benefits (e.g., compliance, brand, employee
                satisfaction) should be described qualitatively in your business
                case, even if they are not fully monetized.
              </p>

              <h3>How long should my time horizon be?</h3>
              <p>
                Choose a horizon that reflects the economic life of the project:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>3–5 years for many IT and process improvement projects</li>
                <li>
                  5–10+ years for capital-intensive construction or
                  infrastructure
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Be conservative: it is better to underestimate long-term
                benefits than to assume they last forever.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I choose a discount rate?</h3>
              <p>Common choices include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Your organization’s
                  <strong>weighted average cost of capital (WACC)</strong>
                </li>
                <li>A standard corporate hurdle rate (e.g., 8–15%)</li>
                <li>A higher rate for riskier or more uncertain projects</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How should I use ROI in project selection?</h3>
              <p>
                ROI is one input into decision-making, not the only one. Use it
                to:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Compare alternative projects or solution options</li>
                <li>Prioritize a portfolio of initiatives</li>
                <li>
                  Support funding requests with clear, quantified benefits
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Combine ROI with strategic alignment, risk, regulatory
                requirements, and capacity constraints to make balanced
                decisions.
              </p>
            </section>
